user.biography: Life with Senior Dog Rescues, Bikini the pig,  Betty the chicken and Tofu the turkey.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Steve Greig on September 18, 2021. May be an image of dog and indoor.

node.text: My house was broken into a couple months ago when the dogs and I were upstairs sleeping. They came in through the back where Bikini was and made their way upstairs to where we were. Luckily, Fernando scared them off. Well, it might have been Raylene, who's really to say. Anyway, after that I had a security system installed so we're all safe, but since that time, Bikini has refused to sleep inside. (Swipe right.) She conveniently found an old dog bed in the garage and inconveniently moved it right into the doorway. Whenever I leave the house I always feel like I should tell her a riddle so she'll let me pass. She still comes in for breakfast and to scratch on things and cause trouble, but absolutely refuses to get into her pink laden toddler bed. I assume once cold weather sets in she will rethink these new found principles, but who knows, I may end up having to move her bed somewhere else in the house. She can definitely be pretty stubborn.

node.text:
I promise I'll start the profile series again soon. Edsel has needed some extra care as he recovers from heart problems and that's where most of my free time has gone. 

In the meantime, one of those photo memory things popped up yesterday of Wolfgang from 11 years ago during our annual trip to Cape Cod. (He's the reason I started adopting senior dogs.)

I remember this so well.  It rained the entire week we were there. After about two days stuck inside I decided that was enough. I bought Wolfgang a raincoat and we spent the rest of the trip outdoors. I took him on bike rides every day on deserted trails, and then we would head to the beach with no one else around.  Sometimes you get exactly what you need.
#thesunwillcomeouttomorrow

I don't care how many times you ask me to bring you a Mai Tai Bikini, it's not gonna happen. 
#poolservicehasclosedfortheseason

node.text:
A few of the gang hanging out with Tofu in the front.
Although Edsel's (far left) progress has been encouraging, his energy level is still very low.  He may just need more time to completely heal, but I'm taking him back to the cardiologist tomorrow for an echocardiogram, just to make sure I'm doing everything right.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Steve Greig on September 06, 2021. May be an image of 1 person, dog and brick wall.

node.text:
Edsel continues to get better every day as he leans on the others for support.
He's eating and wandering around the house, but taking more naps than he used to as he gets his strength back from a heart episode last week. Thank you for all the prayers and concern.
(That's Willamena's Marilyn Monroe impersonation.)

node.text:
Edith lost her battle with cancer this week. There are dogs we meet that deserve everything good in this life and yet ask for so little. She was one of those dogs. 

She was diagnosed several months ago with leukemia. But her prognosis was good because the type of leukemia she had was generally very treatable. I don't know what went wrong. At first the treatments were very effective and she was the happy, dancing, singing Edith I loved so much. But after a while the medicine stopped working and the cancer came back and she got very sick . We tried a different treatment but it did nothing to change its course. On Sunday night she woke me up and I could tell she was uncomfortable. I gave her some pain medicine and consoled her with hugs and strokes and whispers, until I fell asleep as she left this world for the next. 

She came to me from @truefaithfulpetrescue over a year ago. They found her at a shelter set to be euthanized because she had developed a huge tumor and lost most of her hair.  @truefaithfulpetrescue pulled her from the shelter and removed the tumor. Edith got healthy and happy but no one showed any interest in adopting her, so she came to me. I felt like I hit the jackpot. Edith was more than just a good, sweet, happy dog. She was grateful. She would do this strange, offbeat dance while moaning and groaning and singing with pure joy. I gave her the nickname Edith Moaner Lisa. I can't tell you how many zoom meetings I suddenly had to mute because Edith could be heard moaning and singing in the background. Oh how I will miss her presence and those beautiful sounds. Until we meet again sweet, sweet girl

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Steve Greig on August 29, 2021. May be an image of 1 person and outdoors.

node.text:
It's been a hard week.  Edsel got a blood clot and wasn't expected to live.  Then Edith's cancer treatment took quite a toll.  But yesterday was better than the day before.  And today is better than yesterday.  They are both getting a little stronger and I am so grateful. ❤
#givethanks

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Steve Greig on August 25, 2021. May be an image of dog.

node.text:
Loretta is next in the profile series. 

She is 16 years old and has been with me since she was 4. I adopted her long before I started only adopting senior dogs or dogs with disabilities. We both owe her adoption to a dachshund that happened to be out on a walk the day I went to the shelter. I had gone there to adopt that dachshund after noticing him online. But when I arrived a volunteer had taken him out for a walk.  So I wandered around and I happened to see Loretta huddled up in the corner of her cage.  I squatted down by the door and after some coaxing she slowly walked up and gave me one lick and then returned to the far corner. That's all it took I was smitten. The shelter said she was living on the streets for a long time before they were able to catch her. Since then, her shyness had kept her from getting adopted. 

Loretta is the rock of Wolfgang2242. She always eats,  never complains, and other than teeth cleaning she has never been to the vet that I can think of.  Her only quirk is she is terrified of things falling on her from above. I don't know what happened to her in the past,  but if you make any loud noises when she's right below you she runs for cover. She squints when she smiles. She's closest with Edsel although she also seems to have a little crush on Fernando (keeping her options open). But her one true love is cheese.  She can be on an entirely different floor of the house and if someone discreetly starts to open a cheese wrapper in the fridge, it activates some kind of personal Bluetooth system and she'll be at your side with wanton eyes before the cheese ever leaves the package. 

Likes:  The volunteer walk program at the shelter 

Dislikes:  The story of Chicken Little 

Goals:  Head cheese Sommelier in Paris 

Nickname LoRo, Butcher hollaback girl (a nod to Loretta Lynn who's from Butcher Holler)

node.text:
We were horsing around on the beach, challenging each other to foot races, and Carter good naturedly agreed to race Kitty. Carter didn't really try, but Kitty gave it everything she had. 

I don't want to get overly dramatic about how hard this little dog tries in life, and how no one would adopt her because she is incontinent. But man...., just look at her go!
#gokittygo

A good vacation changes you; the way you breathe, the way you think, the way you dress and the way you see yourself. 
Kitty at the cape. 
#chchchchanges
